If you use WordPress as a backend and Next.js as the frontend, you already know why. WordPress gives your content team an editor they already understand. Next.js gives you a fast, modern site. Good combo.
But there are three bugs that show up again and again in this setup. They don’t throw errors. They don’t show up in your console. They just quietly break something, and you spend hours figuring out why.
I’ve run into all three. Here they are, in plain language, with the fix for each one.
1. Your Image Field Shows Up as Empty (Even Though It’s Not)
Press enter or click to view image in full size

What happens: You add an image in WordPress using an ACF field. It looks fine in wp-admin. But when you pull that data through WPGraphQL, the image field comes back empty. Nothing. No error either — it just doesn’t show up.
Why this happens: ACF image fields have a setting called “Return Format.” You can set it to:

• Image Array

• Image ID

• Image URL
If it’s set to “Image URL,” WPGraphQL doesn’t know what to do with it. It can’t build the full image object you need, so it just gives you nothing back.
The fix: Change the return format to Image ID. Then let WPGraphQL do the rest of the work for you:
graphql
query GetPageHero {
page(id: "123", idType: DATABASE_ID) {
heroImage {
node {
sourceUrl
altText
}
}
}
}Sometimes this still doesn’t fix it. If that happens, check for an orphaned image ID — this means the field is pointing to an image that got deleted or lost during a migration. In that case, you need to add a simple check on the backend that logs which posts have this problem, so you’re not guessing:
php
add_filter('graphql_resolve_field', function ($result, $source, $args, $context, $info, $type_name, $field_key) {
if ($field_key === 'heroImage' && empty($result)) {
$attachment_id = get_field('hero_image', $source->ID, false);
if ($attachment_id && !get_post($attachment_id)) {
error_log("Broken image ID on post {$source->ID}");
}
}
return $result;
}, 10, 7);That one log line saves a lot of guesswork later.
2. “Empty” Fields That Aren’t Actually Empty
Press enter or click to view image in full size

What happens: You write a simple check like this:
javascript
{content && <div>{content}</div>}You expect this to hide the block when there’s no content. But it still shows up — an empty box on the page, or weird spacing where nothing should be.
Why this happens: WordPress rich text fields almost never come back truly empty. Even when an editor leaves a field blank, WordPress usually saves it as <p></p>. That's a string with actual characters in it. In JavaScript, any non-empty string counts as "true," so your check passes, and you end up rendering an empty box.
The fix: Don’t check the raw content. Strip the HTML tags first, then check what’s left:

• If nothing is left after removing tags, treat it as empty

• If there’s real text left, show the block
javascript
function hasContent(html) {
if (!html) return false;
const stripped = html.replace(/<[^>]*>/g, '').trim();
return stripped.length > 0;
}javascript
{hasContent(page.description) && (
<div dangerouslySetInnerHTML={{ __html: page.description }} />
)}This bug is annoying because it looks fine in wp-admin. The field looks empty to the editor. It only breaks the layout once it hits your frontend.
3. Your Menu Breaks the Moment Someone Edits It
Press enter or click to view image in full size

What happens: Your navigation menu works fine while you’re building the site. Then a content editor adds a new menu item or moves one around in wp-admin. Suddenly, the frontend menu doesn’t update — or it throws an error, or the new item just doesn’t show up.
Why this happens: WPGraphQL doesn’t send your menu as a neat, nested list. It sends every menu item as a flat item, and each one just has a parentId pointing to its parent. If your code assumes the menu already comes nested (like WordPress does by default in its own theme system), any new or reordered item can break that assumption.
It works in development because your test menu never hit that edge case. Then someone adds a submenu in production, and it falls apart.
The fix: Don’t assume the shape of the data. Build the tree yourself, every time:
javascript
function buildMenuTree(items) {
const map = new Map(items.map(item => [item.id, { ...item, children: [] }]));
const tree = []; map.forEach(item => {
if (item.parentId && map.has(item.parentId)) {
map.get(item.parentId).children.push(item);
} else {
tree.push(item);
}
}); return tree;
}If you’re using Next.js with static generation, also set up a short revalidation window. That way, menu changes in wp-admin reach the live site without needing a full redeploy.
What These Three Bugs Have in Common
None of them threw an error. That’s the real problem. Each one made me trace data through three layers — WordPress, then WPGraphQL, then Next.js — just to find where things quietly broke.
The lesson I keep coming back to:

• Don’t assume something exists just because it’s in the CMS

• Check what actually comes through the API, not what you expect to come through

• Handle the empty/broken case on purpose, instead of hoping it never happens
If your headless WordPress + Next.js site is acting strange in ways you can’t explain, these three spots are a good place to start looking.

I build headless WordPress, Next.js, and Shopify sites at Zillionera, a web development studio in India. If you’re stuck on something similar, feel free to reach out.
